Drag & Drop

 

This feature has been implemented to facilitate the movement of data between different panes.

For example, the user wishes to add a breakpoint at a particular function, but cannot remember the exact name/spelling of it.

The user would then browse through the Workspace pane to find the function, and then ‘drag’ the function name across to the Breakpoint pane and ‘drop’ it. This would add a breakpoint at the address of the function.

 

Drag & drop operations are executed by moving the mouse over the information to be dragged and holding down the left mouse button. The mouse is then moved (with the button still held down) over to the pane on which it is to be dropped. The mouse button is then released and the data is copied into the new pane.

When the mouse is dragging data, the arrow cursor will change to indicate that data is being dragged.

The outcome of a drag & drop operation varies according to the pane from which the data was dragged, and that which it is dropped on. See the table below for a diagram of the possible combinations:

NOTES

·         Goto operations (dragging on to source pane) work on functions only at present

·         Drag from the memory pane to a different type of pane only works from addresses of the start of an object (e.g. To see this, drag a function or variable onto memory pane, then drag from memory to watch – only dragging from the address of the variable will be correctly evaluated and added to the Watch pane). Dragging to another memory pane will work with any address.

·         On the memory pane, dragging must be from the address at the left of the pane.

·         On the source pane, text selections are dragged. If multiple lines are selected, only the first line is dragged. Leading spaces are removed.

·         Workspace pane. Dragging classes to the Breakpoint or Watch panes will add all methods or members within the class respectively

·         If a class or structure is added to the Watch and is expanded, the members of the item may be dropped onto the Watch pane to add a watch expression for just that member.
E.g. With the code fragment below (Drag & Drop and the Source Pane section), if ‘front_end_game_data’ was added to the Watch pane and expanded. Dragging the ‘selected_country’ member variable and dropping it back on the Watch pane would add a new Watch expression for
’front_end_game_data.selected_country’.

·         In the Watch pane, for dragging & dropping onto itself the cursor must move by at least the height of the line for the drop to be carried out. This is to avoid accidental drag operations (e.g. moving the mouse when clicking to expand a class or structure).

·         Dragging a class member from the Workspace pane to any pane will concatenate the class name with the member name.
E.g. Dragging an item called ‘m_my_member_variable’ from class CMyClass in the workspace pane would create the expression CMyClass::m_my_member_variable for dropping onto a pane which could then be evaluated by the Watch pane.

 

 

Drag & Drop and the Source Pane

To drag information from the Source pane, a text selection should be made. The mouse button should then be held down with the cursor over the selected data. This can then be dragged in the normal way. If the selection covers multiple lines, only the first line will be ‘dropped’.

For example, selecting and dragging ‘front_end_game_data.selected_country’ in the code to the Watch pane would add this class member to the Watch pane.

However, selecting just the ‘front_end_game_data’ part of the line and dropping this in the Watch pane would add the actual class as a Watch variable, allowing it to be expanded to show all member variables.

 

main()

{

    front_end_game_data.selected_country = 0;

    front_end_game_data.selected_game_mode = WWR_TIME_ATTACK_MODE;

    front_end_game_data.selected_class = NOVICE_CLASS;

    front_end_game_data.selected_car = WWR_DOUBLE_MOON;

    ……………………

    ……………………

    ……………………

 

}

 

 

Pane Modifier Keys

When dropping data onto a pane, it may be desirable to create a new pane rather than add to the existing one (e.g. load a source file into a new pane while leaving the exist source pane as-is).

To enable this, three keyboard modifiers (CTRL, SHIFT and ALT) have been utilised. These keys are not currently user-configurable.

Holding one of these keys down while dropping data onto a pane activates the modifier.

  • The Control key splits the destination pane vertically and drops data into the new pane (beneath the existing one)
  • Shift splits horizontally and drops into the rightmost pane.
  • Finally, the Alt key creates a new (floating) pane for the dropped data.

 

If data is dragged over a pane that cannot accept the data (or over an area of the screen that doesn’t contain any panes), the cursor will change to show a No Entry sign.

Releasing the mouse button while this cursor is displayed will abort the drag operation and discard the data.
